    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Prozac Is Not a Joke</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dana D Lichty letter says prominent photo of prescription bottle labeled 'Prozac' nestled in baseball glove trivializes an illness that plays havoc with lives of 15 million Americans (Oct 15 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Quaking at the Thought of a Subway Series'' (news article, Oct. 15):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Quaking at the Thought of a Subway Series'' (news article, Oct. 15):</p>
        <p>Your prominent photo of a prescription bottle labeled ''Prozac'' nestled in a baseball glove trivializes an illness that plays havoc with the lives of 15 million Americans, including me.</p>
        <p>Making Prozac a joke is in poor taste. Moreover, it is an injustice to the one in eight people like me who need treatment for depression at some point in their lives.</p>
        <p>For those lucky enough to afford and successfully take them, Prozac and other selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors are not an amusing antidote to the stress of a sports event. S.S.R.I.'s are lifesavers. People who are challenged by depression need everyone to take this illness seriously, and treat with respect the medications that help control its symptoms.</p>
        <p>DANA D. LICHTY  Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., Oct. 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
